{"session_id":"svc-1778083842725161338","seq":0,"type":"session.start","ts":"2026-05-06T16:10:46.80382537Z","data":{"provider":"","model":"gpt-5.4-mini","resolved_harness":"codex","harness_source":"auto_route","resolved_model":"gpt-5.4-mini","work_dir":"/tmp/ddx-exec-wt/.execute-bead-wt-ddx-cce893be-20260506T161039-4745079a","max_iterations":0,"prompt":"\u003cexecute-bead\u003e\n  \u003cinstructions\u003e\nYou are executing one bead inside an isolated DDx execution worktree. The bead\u0026#39;s \u0026lt;description\u0026gt; and \u0026lt;acceptance\u0026gt; are the completion contract — every AC must be provably satisfied by a specific code, test, or file you can point to after your commit.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;## Step 0: size check\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;The bead is too big when any of these holds:\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;- More than ~6 ACs spanning unrelated subsystems.\u0026#xA;- AC mixes design, implementation, integration tests, and docs as separate top-level deliverables.\u0026#xA;- Description names multiple feature-sized sub-pieces.\u0026#xA;- More than ~500 lines across more than ~5 files in unrelated packages.\u0026#xA;- If the bead description exceeds 8000 bytes, treat Step 0 as a split-first pass and favor child-bead scoping before implementation.\u0026#xA;- Auto-decomposition is capped at depth 2: root beads may split once, decomposed children may split once more, and third-level splits must be rejected with an explanation.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;If too big, decompose — do not attempt the work:\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;1. `ddx bead create` for each child slice (focused title, description, AC; copy parent\u0026#39;s labels and spec-id).\u0026#xA;2. `ddx bead dep add \u0026lt;child-id\u0026gt; \u0026lt;parent-id\u0026gt;` to record edges.\u0026#xA;3. `ddx bead update \u0026lt;parent-id\u0026gt; --notes \u0026#39;decomposed into \u0026lt;child-ids\u0026gt;\u0026#39;` so the decomposition is visible.\u0026#xA;4. Write `.ddx/executions/20260506T161039-4745079a/no_changes_rationale.txt` listing each child ID and slice, then stop.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;A clean decomposition is a successful attempt. Do not mix partial implementation with decomposition.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;## How to work\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;- Read first. If the bead names files, specs, or prior beads, read them before editing — do not guess.\u0026#xA;- Cross-reference each AC against concrete evidence (test name, file path, function) before committing. If you cannot point at it, it is not done.\u0026#xA;- Run the project\u0026#39;s test and lint commands before committing. **Do not commit red code** — fix failures first.\u0026#xA;- Stage with `git add \u0026lt;specific-paths\u0026gt;`; never `git add -A` (the worktree may have unrelated WIP).\u0026#xA;- Commit exactly once when green; conventional-commit subject ending with `[\u0026lt;bead-id\u0026gt;]`. Stop after the commit.\u0026#xA;- Do not modify files outside the bead\u0026#39;s scope.\u0026#xA;- If you cannot finish, write `.ddx/executions/20260506T161039-4745079a/no_changes_rationale.txt` (what is done, what blocks, what a follow-up needs) before exiting. No commit and no rationale ⇒ DDx records `no_evidence_produced`. A well-justified no_changes beats a bad commit.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;## no_changes contract\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;If you write `.ddx/executions/20260506T161039-4745079a/no_changes_rationale.txt`, it MUST carry one of:\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;- `verification_command: \u0026lt;one-line shell command\u0026gt;` — the loop runs it (cwd = project root, 60s); exit 0 closes the bead, non-zero rejects.\u0026#xA;- `status: needs_investigation` + `reason: \u0026lt;why\u0026gt;` — bead stays open for triage.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;Bare rationales (\u0026#34;nothing to do\u0026#34;) are rejected.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;## Reports\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;Freestanding artifacts (investigation reports, findings docs) go under `.ddx/executions/20260506T161039-4745079a/` (the per-attempt evidence directory under `.ddx/executions/`). **Never write reports to `/tmp` or any path outside the repository** — out-of-repo paths are invisible to the post-merge reviewer and cause BLOCK on missing evidence. If the bead names a specific in-repo path, use it; else default to `.ddx/executions/20260506T161039-4745079a/\u0026lt;short-name\u0026gt;.md`. Stage and commit the report alongside code.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;## Bead overrides project defaults\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;The bead description and AC override CLAUDE.md, AGENTS.md, and conservative project defaults (YAGNI, DOWITYTD, no-docs-unless-asked) in this worktree — write whatever the bead asks for.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;## Review gate\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;- The review is a gate, not an escape hatch — meet every AC in this pass.\u0026#xA;- Address every BLOCKING `\u0026lt;review-findings\u0026gt;` item; do not declare `no_changes` with blocking findings open.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;## Constraints\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;- Work only inside this execution worktree.\u0026#xA;- Keep `.ddx/executions/` intact — DDx uses it as execution evidence.\u0026#xA;- **Never run `ddx init`** — the workspace is initialized; running it corrupts the bead queue.\u0026#xA;- Do not modify files outside the bead\u0026#39;s named scope.\u0026#xA;- Do not rewrite CLAUDE.md, AGENTS.md, or other project-instructions files unless the bead asks.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;## When the work is done\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;After the commit succeeds and every AC is verified, stop. Return control to the orchestrator — do not keep exploring or testing.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;## Decomposition depth cap\u0026#xA;This bead is already at decomposition depth 3. Do not create another child layer; if it is still too large, reject the split with a short explanation and write no_changes_rationale.txt instead.\u0026#xA;\n  \u003c/instructions\u003e\n  \u003cbead id=\"ddx-cce893be\"\u003e\n    \u003ctitle\u003edocs: report recent failed attempt causes and readiness checkability\u003c/title\u003e\n    \u003cdescription\u003e\nPROBLEM\u0026#xA;Recent `ddx work` attempts failed repeatedly, but the causes are mixed together in tracker events and execution bundles. Operators cannot tell which failures are bead-readiness defects versus provider, host resource, git, review, close-policy, or unknown failures.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;ROOT CAUSE WITH FILE:LINE\u0026#xA;- `.ddx/beads.jsonl` stores execute-bead, bead-quality, routing, review, and cost events in the same per-bead event streams; recent events include provider exhaustion, review transport, ENOSPC, git index lock, no_changes, and tests_red-like checkpoint failures without a durable cross-attempt report.\u0026#xA;- `cli/internal/agent/execute_bead_loop.go:670` logs pre-claim intake failures inline and continues claiming, leaving the analysis spread across terminal output and bead events.\u0026#xA;- `cli/internal/agent/execute_bead_loop.go:732-751` logs pre-dispatch lint failures separately from intake, so one operator-visible failure taxonomy is not available.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;PROPOSED FIX\u0026#xA;Create a durable report under `docs/helix/06-iterate/` from recent `.ddx/beads.jsonl` events and `.ddx/executions/*` bundles. The report must group failed beads by estimated cause, include examples, state whether each cause is checkable by bead readiness before claim, and identify the owning follow-up surface.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;NON-SCOPE\u0026#xA;Do not change specs, skills, Go code, tracker state beyond this bead, or live worker behavior.\n    \u003c/description\u003e\n    \u003cacceptance\u003e\n1. Report defines the evidence window by timestamp range, execution directory range, or both.\u0026#xA;2. Report lists failed bead IDs with observed error snippets and estimated causes.\u0026#xA;3. Report consolidates causes into bead readiness, system readiness, post-attempt, close-policy, and unknown buckets.\u0026#xA;4. Each bucket states whether bead-lifecycle readiness can check it before claim.\u0026#xA;5. Report identifies follow-up spec/code surfaces for each bucket.\u0026#xA;6. Documentation-only waiver is stated in closing notes; no new Go test is required unless the report adds generated references.\u0026#xA;7. `lefthook run pre-commit` passes.\n    \u003c/acceptance\u003e\n    \u003clabels\u003ephase:2, area:docs, area:agent, kind:analysis, reliability, bead-quality, adr:023, spec:FEAT-010\u003c/labels\u003e\n    \u003cmetadata parent=\"ddx-a9d130d0\" spec-id=\"ADR-023\" base-rev=\"d066b248c36184afc0fa400b30322d29823a5f3d\" bundle=\".ddx/executions/20260506T161039-4745079a\"/\u003e\n  \u003c/bead\u003e\n  \u003cgoverning\u003e\n    \u003cref id=\"ADR-023\" path=\"docs/helix/02-design/adr/ADR-023-bead-lifecycle-quality-policy.md\"\u003eADR-023: Bead Lifecycle Quality Policy\u003c/ref\u003e\n  \u003c/governing\u003e\n\u003c/execute-bead\u003e\n","metadata":{"attempt_id":"20260506T161039-4745079a","base_rev":"d066b248c36184afc0fa400b30322d29823a5f3d","bead_id":"ddx-cce893be","bundle_path":".ddx/executions/20260506T161039-4745079a","correlation_id":"ddx-cce893be:20260506T161039-4745079a","prompt_file":".ddx/executions/20260506T161039-4745079a/prompt.md","prompt_sha":"a678b26f6568a897f4fbd7f01b40831b82f282a08aba10495efda116dabbbeab","role":"implementer","session_id":"eb-66806814","worker_id":""}}}
